      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The article on Sept. 13 entitled ''Mixed Record Emerges From Auction Sales of City Houses'' was a welcome change from the romanticized reports on the auction process that have occasionally appeared in The New York Times and in other publications.</p>
        <p>We want to point out, however, that we not only inspected our house prior to the auction, but we also obtained an engineer's report on its condition. It is important to note that no matter how much homework auction buyers do, they are still likely to be faced with long delays and unexpected costs, largely because of the way the city's auction-related programs are structured.</p>
        <p>To clarify another point, the delayed progress payments made by the Dime Savings Bank did not result in our contractor's walking off the job. Our relationship did, understandably, deteriorate when scheduled payments failed to materialize.  MARIAN L. LUMMIS  MICHAEL J. PIONE  Brooklyn</p>
      </block>
